{
  "doc_id": "16898",
  "text": "The importance of the 5-hydroxytryptamine (5-HT; serotonin) system in the control of food intake and body mass has been recognised for many years and alterations in central serotonergic activity have been observed in obese humans, non-human primates and rodents [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . 5-HT is a potent anorectic signal that influences food intake in the mature brain by acting predominantly via 5-HT 2C R to regulate the key energy balance mediator, pro-opiomelanocortin (POMC), within the arcuate nucleus of the hypothalamus (ARC; [CITATION_4] Burke et al., 2014) . Indeed, disruption of the 5-HT 2C R gene (Htr2c) specifically expressed on POMC neurons programmes hyperphagia and obesity when animals are fed a high-fat diet [CITATION_5] . In addition to playing an important role in energy balance and body mass, 5-HT acts as a trophic factor during fetal brain development in rodents, regulating cell migration, proliferation, maturation and axonal growth [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . The long-term effects of disturbances in the 5-HT system during early life on obesity risk are, however, not fully defined.",
